  "text": "## Grafana Configuration Loading System\n\nGrafana's configuration system is implemented primarily in `pkg/setting/` with the main entry point being the `Cfg.Load()` function in `pkg/setting/setting.go:1138`. This orchestrates the entire configuration loading pipeline.\n\n### 1. INI File Parser and Configuration Loading\n\nThe configuration uses the `gopkg.in/ini.v1` library for INI file parsing. The loading sequence in `loadConfiguration()` (line 963) is:\n\n1. **Load defaults**: `conf/defaults.ini` is loaded first as the base configuration\n2. **Apply command-line default properties**: Command-line arguments with `default.` prefix override defaults\n3. **Load custom config**: If `conf/custom.ini` exists, it merges with the default configuration\n4. **Apply environment variable overrides**: GF_* environment variables override INI file values\n5. **Apply command-line property overrides**: Direct command-line arguments override everything\n6. **Expand variables**: Environment variables within config values are expanded\n\n### 2. Environment Variable Override Chain\n\nThe `applyEnvVariableOverrides()` function (line 744) implements the dynamic override mechanism. It iterates through all sections and keys in the INI file, constructs environment variable names using the `EnvKey()` function (line 855), and applies values if the environment variable is set.\n\nEnvironment variable format: `GF_[SECTION]_[KEY]` where dots and hyphens are replaced with underscores and converted to uppercase. For example, `GF_SERVER_HTTP_PORT` overrides `[server] http_port`.\n\nThe `DynamicSection` struct (line 1568) and its `Key()` method (line 1576) provide runtime environment variable override capability through `SectionWithEnvOverrides()` (line 1605), allowing services to dynamically override configuration keys during runtime.\n\n### 3. Default Values Per Section\n\nDefault values are defined in `conf/defaults.ini` and loaded via `ini.Load()`. Section-specific configuration is parsed through dedicated functions:\n\n- `readSecuritySettings()` (line 1613) - security section defaults\n- `readServerSettings()` (line 1919) - server section defaults  \n- `readUserSettings()` (line 1791) - users section defaults\n- `readAuthSettings()` (line 1696) - auth section defaults\n- `readDataProxySettings()` in `pkg/setting/setting_data_proxy.go` (line 11) - dataproxy section with defaults like `defaultDataProxyRowLimit`\n- Multiple other `setting_*.go` files for specific sections (azure, smtp, storage, etc.)\n\nEach read function calls `MustInt()`, `MustString()`, `MustBool()`, `MustDuration()` methods on INI keys with fallback defaults when values are absent.\n\n### 4. Sensitive Configuration Value Masking\n\nThe `RedactedValue()` function (line 660) masks sensitive configuration values before they are returned to clients. It uses pattern matching on uppercased key names to identify sensitive keys:\n\n**Sensitive patterns matched**:\n- PASSWORD, SECRET, PRIVATE_KEY, SECRET_KEY\n- CERTIFICATE, ACCOUNT_KEY, ENCRYPTION_KEY\n- VAULT_TOKEN, CLIENT_SECRET\n- ENTERPRISE_LICENSE, API_DB_PASS\n- TOKEN (exact match via regex `^TOKEN$`)\n- ID_FORWARDING_TOKEN, AUTHENTICATION_TOKEN, AUTH_TOKEN, RENDERER_TOKEN, API_TOKEN, WEBHOOK_TOKEN, INSTALL_TOKEN\n- PROVIDER_CONFIG\n\n**Exceptions** for services that explicitly need visible values: RUDDERSTACK, APPLICATION_INSIGHTS, SENTRY\n\n**URL masking**: The function also calls `RedactedURL()` (line 711) to mask sensitive information in URLs (passwords in connection strings).\n\nAll values are redacted to `\"*********\"` (constant `RedactedPassword` at line 46) when sensitive patterns match.\n\n### 5. Settings API Endpoint (`/api/admin/settings`)\n\nThe endpoint handler in `pkg/api/admin.go:29` (`AdminGetSettings()`) retrieves current settings through the following chain:\n\n1. Calls `hs.SettingsProvider.Current()` which returns a `SettingsBag`\n2. The `OSSImpl.Current()` method in `pkg/setting/provider.go:118` iterates through all INI file sections and keys\n3. **Critical masking step**: For each key-value pair, it calls `RedactedValue(EnvKey(section.Name(), key.Name()), key.Value())` before adding to the settings bag\n4. Returns filtered results through `getAuthorizedSettings()` which applies access control filters based on user permissions\n\n### 6. Type Definitions\n\n**SettingsBag** (`pkg/setting/provider.go:97`): `map[string]map[string]string` - sections to key-value pairs\n\n**VerboseSettingsBag** (`pkg/setting/provider.go:101`): `map[string]map[string]map[VerboseSourceType]string` - includes source tracking (DB or System) for each setting\n\n**VerboseSourceType** constants: `DB` and `System` indicating where each setting came from\n\nThe configuration system ensures sensitive values are masked at the API boundary while maintaining full internal access to configuration values for backend services."
}

